JOINING DATA WITH DPLYR: LEFT JOINS AND RIGHT JOINS

Load the Dplyr package and read the tables:

library(dplyr) 
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
inventories <- readRDS("inventories.rds")
inventory_parts <- readRDS("inventory_parts.rds")

Combine inventories and inventory_parts using inner_join:

inventory_parts_joined <- inventories %>%
  inner_join(inventory_parts, by = c("id" = "inventory_id"))

For simplicity, remove the id and version variables since we don’t need them. Arrange to sort in order of quantity, which represents how many of a piece appear in each set:

inventory_parts_joined <- inventory_parts_joined %>%
  select(-id, -version) %>%
  arrange(desc(quantity))

2.1 The left_join verb

What’s the difference between the Batmobile and the Batwing? They are both vehicles owned by the superhero Batman, though Batmobile is a car and Batwing can fly. With the datasets we’re using, we can look at what parts are included in one of their LEGO sets but not the other.

Extract just 2 LEGO sets “Batmobile” and “Batwing” based on their set numbers:

batmobile <- inventory_parts_joined %>%
  filter(set_num == "7784-1") %>%
  select(-set_num)
batwing <- inventory_parts_joined %>%
  filter(set_num == "70916-1") %>%
  select(-set_num)

This results in 2 new tables with each observation isn’t just a part, but a combination of a part and color.

The joined table shows that the first part appears 28 times in the Batmobile set, but only 17 times in the Batwing set.

What if we just want to keep parts that are in the Batmobile but not the Batwing? An inner join keeps only observations that appear in both tables. Keep all the observations in one table with left_join verb:

batmobile %>%
  left_join(batwing, by = c("part_num", "color_id"),
            suffix = c("_batmobile", "_batwing"))
## # A tibble: 173 x 4
##    part_num color_id quantity_batmobile quantity_batwing
##    <chr>       <dbl>              <dbl>            <dbl>
##  1 3023           72                 62               NA
##  2 2780            0                 28               17
##  3 50950           0                 28                2
##  4 3004           71                 26                2
##  5 43093           1                 25                6
##  6 3004            0                 23                4
##  7 3010            0                 21               NA
##  8 30363           0                 21               NA
##  9 32123b         14                 19               NA
## 10 3622            0                 18                2
## # ... with 163 more rows

The pieces that didn’t appear in inner_join now show up in the first table.

Left join means keeping all the observations in the first, or “left”, of the two tables, whether or not it occurs in the second, or “right” table.

Extract two other LEGO sets “Millennium Falcom” and “Star Destroyer” based on their set numbers:

millennium_falcom <- inventory_parts_joined %>% 
  filter(set_num == "7965-1")
star_destroyer <- inventory_parts_joined %>%
  filter(set_num == "75190-1")

Combine the two sets by “part” and “color” using left_join:

millennium_falcom %>% 
  left_join(star_destroyer, by = c("part_num", "color_id"),
            suffix = c("_falcon", "_star_destroyer"))

What if joining two datasets by color alone?

Aggregate Millennium Falcon and Star Destroyer for the total quantity in each part:

millennium_falcom_colors <- millennium_falcom %>%
  group_by(color_id) %>%
  summarise(total_quantity = sum(quantity))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
star_destroyer_colors <- star_destroyer %>%
  group_by(color_id) %>%
  summarise(total_quantity = sum(quantity))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

millennium_falcom_colors %>%

Left joins are really great for testing your assumption about a dataset and ensuring your data has an integrity. For example, the inventories table has a version column, for when a LEGO kit gets some kind of change or update. Assume that all sets would have at least a version 1.

inventory_version_1 <- inventories %>%
  filter(version == 1)

Test the assumption by joining versions to sets:

sets <- readRDS("sets.rds")
sets %>% left_join(inventory_version_1, by = "set_num") %>%
  # filter where version is na
  filter(is.na(version))
## # A tibble: 1 x 6
##   set_num name       year theme_id    id version
##   <chr>   <chr>     <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 40198-1 Ludo game  2018      598    NA      NA

It looks like there are cases where a set does not have an original version.

2.2 The right_join verb

The right joins are mirror images of left joins. A right join keeps all the observations in the second (or right) table, whether or not they appear in the first table.

batmobile %>%
  right_join(batwing, by = c("part_num", "color_id"),
             suffix = c("_batmobile", "_batwing"))
## # A tibble: 312 x 4
##    part_num color_id quantity_batmobile quantity_batwing
##    <chr>       <dbl>              <dbl>            <dbl>
##  1 2780            0                 28               17
##  2 50950           0                 28                2
##  3 3004           71                 26                2
##  4 43093           1                 25                6
##  5 3004            0                 23                4
##  6 3622            0                 18                2
##  7 4286            0                 16                1
##  8 3039            0                 12                2
##  9 4274           71                 12                7
## 10 3001            0                 11                4
## # ... with 302 more rows

With the right join, we see NA in the quantity_batmobile column, but not in quantity_batwing.

Use right join to determine how often each theme appears among the sets in the database, for example, calculate the number of sets that has each theme id:

sets %>%

The useful information for theme_id is in another table called themes. Import and examine this table:

themes <- readRDS("themes.rds")

Use inner join to add theme name for more info:

sets %>%
  count(theme_id, sort = TRUE) %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id"))

2.3 Replace NA

For this data those NAs appeared in count result should really be zeros. Import the tidyr package to use replace_na function:

library(tidyr)

Replace NA with 0:

sets %>%
  count(theme_id, sort = TRUE) %>%
  right_join(themes, by = c("theme_id" = "id")) %>%
  replace_na(list(n = 0))
## # A tibble: 665 x 4
##    theme_id     n name              parent_id
##       <dbl> <dbl> <chr>                 <dbl>
##  1      501   122 Gear                     NA
##  2      494   111 Friends                  NA
##  3      435    94 Ninjago                  NA
##  4      505    94 Basic Set               504
##  5      632    93 Town                    504
##  6      371    89 Supplemental            365
##  7      497    86 Books                    NA
##  8      503    82 Key Chain               501
##  9      516    78 Duplo and Explore       507
## 10      220    72 City                    217
## # ... with 655 more rows

replace_na() is often used after a left or right join. For example, read the tables parts and part_categories:

parts <- readRDS("parts.rds")
part_categories <- readRDS("part_categories.rds")

Sometimes you will want to do some processing before you do a join, and prioritize keeping the second (right) table’s rows instead.

parts %>%
  count(part_cat_id, sort = TRUE) %>%
  right_join(part_categories, by = c("part_cat_id" = "id")) %>%
  # filter for where the column n is NA
  filter(is.na(n == TRUE ))
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   part_cat_id     n name   
##         <dbl> <int> <chr>  
## 1          66    NA Modulex

Count before right join because we don’t only want to know the count of part_cat_id in parts but we also want to know if there is any part_cat_id not presents in parts. Then filter to find an instance where a part category is present in one table, but missing from the other table. It is important to understand which entries would be impacted by replace_na(), so that we know which entries we would be omitting by using that function.

Replace NA with 0:

parts %>%
  count(part_cat_id, sort = TRUE) %>%
  right_join(part_categories, by = c("part_cat_id" = "id")) %>%
  replace_na(list(n = 0))
## # A tibble: 64 x 3
##    part_cat_id     n name

##  3          59  1565 Minifig Heads                          
##  4          27   937 Minifig Accessories

2.4 Joining tables to themselves

In the themes table, beside theme_id and name, there is also a parent_id column. This indicates a hierarchical table.

themes
## # A tibble: 665 x 3
##       id name           parent_id
##    <dbl> <chr>              <dbl>
##  1     1 Technic               NA
##  2     2 Arctic Technic         1
##  3     3 Competition            1
##  4     4 Expert Builder         1
##  5     5 Model                  1
##  6     6 Airport                5
##  7     7 Construction           5
##  8     8 Farm                   5
##  9     9 Fire                   5
## 10    10 Harbor                 5
## # ... with 655 more rows

For example, the themes “Arctic Technic”, “Competition”, “Expert Builder” and “Model” all have the parent ID 1. Based on the first column, we can see that that ID corresponds to the first theme called “Technic”.

By joining a table to itself we can explore the relationship between themes and parents. By using the parent_id on the left to match the id column on the right, we end up with a table of child-parent relationships.

themes %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("parent_id" = "id"),
             suffix = c("_child", "_parent"))
## # A tibble: 544 x 5
##       id name_child     parent_id name_parent parent_id_parent
##    <dbl> <chr>              <dbl> <chr>                  <dbl>
##  1     2 Arctic Technic         1 Technic                   NA
##  2     3 Competition            1 Technic                   NA
##  3     4 Expert Builder         1 Technic                   NA
##  4     5 Model                  1 Technic                   NA
##  5     6 Airport                5 Model                      1
##  6     7 Construction           5 Model                      1
##  7     8 Farm                   5 Model                      1
##  8     9 Fire                   5 Model                      1
##  9    10 Harbor                 5 Model                      1
## 10    11 Off-Road               5 Model                      1
## # ... with 534 more rows

Examine other LEGO sets that are themed around the fantasy series “The Lords of the Rings”.

themes %>%

             suffix = c("_child", "_parent")) %>%
  filter(name_child == "The Lord of the Rings")
## # A tibble: 1 x 5

Find out all of the children of that theme:

themes %>%

Based on all this, we start understanding the shape of the data.

Some themes might not have any children at all, which means they will not be included in the inner join. Left join a table to itself:

themes %>%
  left_join(themes, by = c("id" = "parent_id"), suffix = c("_parent", "_child")) %>%
  filter(is.na(id_child) == TRUE)
## # A tibble: 586 x 5
##       id name_parent    parent_id id_child name_child
##    <dbl> <chr>              <dbl>    <dbl> <chr>     
##  1     2 Arctic Technic         1       NA <NA>      
##  2     3 Competition            1       NA <NA>      
##  3     4 Expert Builder         1       NA <NA>      
##  4     6 Airport                5       NA <NA>      
##  5     7 Construction           5       NA <NA>      
##  6     8 Farm                   5       NA <NA>      
##  7     9 Fire                   5       NA <NA>      
##  8    10 Harbor                 5       NA <NA>      
##  9    11 Off-Road               5       NA <NA>      
## 10    12 Race                   5       NA <NA>      
## # ... with 576 more rows

From this table, we learned that there are 586 themes in total that do not have any child themes.

Go one step further by inner joining themes to a filtered version of itself again to establish a connection between the last join’s children and their children (or parents’ grandchildren):

themes %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("id" = "parent_id"), 
             suffix = c("_parent", "_child")) %>%
  inner_join(themes, by = c("id_child" = "parent_id"), 
             suffix = c("_parent", "_grandchild"))
